english:
  title: Postscript to the Song of Verifying the Way
  author: Lee Suk
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The present copy of the Song of Verifying the Way bears the calligraphy of Zhao Mengfu, the Academician of Wuxing. It was inscribed with a colophon by Fan Rengui, Minister of Lin'an, and again by Zhao Zizhong, the Awaiting Appointment official, who viewed it at the Hall of Pine and Moon and added his mark. From the year Bingchen of the Yanyou era to the year Yiwei of the Zhizheng era spans some forty years. That the Zhao family, father and son, became patrons of this work has only deepened the faith of all who behold it, putting to shame those charlatans who peddle their names through association. The former abbot Yuktian Daryun brought this treasure back to the Eastern Kingdom, where it has now rested for twenty years. The former Minister Ugong has conceived the plan to widely disseminate it, intending now to have it carved upon wooden blocks. Yuktian entreated me to set down this record.

    I have heard it said that the refinement and brilliance of Zhao Mengfu shine forth as luminously in his brushstrokes as in his very nature, while the grace and sublimity of his verse harmonize with the elegance of his being. Observing these marks of his brush, one can indeed perceive the man himself. That Ugong now seeks to spread this work widely—it is not merely Yuktian's good fortune. Should the Zhao family, father and son, come to know of it, they would surely say: "Though our teachings took wing toward the west, our Way has now also reached the east." What greater joy could there be in such fortune? Thus I take gladness in recording these words at its end.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Zhao Mengfu (1254-1322) was a renowned Yuan dynasty scholar-official, master calligrapher, and poet. His work was highly esteemed and collected throughout East Asia.
  - key: ''
    value: The Song of Verifying the Way is a Buddhist didactic text; this postscript celebrates both the text and Zhao Mengfu's calligraphic rendering of it.
  - key: ''
    value: The dates mentioned (1326 to 1375) span a period of renewed cultural exchange between Yuan China and Korea, with Buddhist texts playing a significant role in this transmission.
